{
  "risk_analysis": "As a landlord-operations analyst (and not a licensed attorney), I must highlight that the absence of a written lease document introduces significant legal risk and uncertainty. Without the lease, we cannot verify if utilities are contractually defined as 'additional rent' under Fla. Stat. 83.43(6). If they are not, demanding them as rent or using them as a basis for non-payment notices is legally defective. Additionally, assuming abandonment under Fla. Stat. 83.595 is highly risky; if the tenant has not actually abandoned the property and the landlord retakes possession, the landlord could face severe statutory liability for unlawful self-help under Fla. Stat. 83.67. There is also a strict 30-day statutory window under Fla. Stat. 83.49 to notify the tenant via certified mail of any intent to impose a claim on the security deposit for unpaid utilities or rent; missing this window results in forfeiture of the deposit claim. Lastly, disposing of any left-behind personal property without following the formal notice and storage timelines in Fla. Stat. 715.10-715.111 exposes the landlord to liability for civil conversion.",
  "recommended_next_steps": [
    "Locate and thoroughly review the written lease agreement to determine if utilities are explicitly defined as additional rent, and check for any early-termination or personal property waiver clauses.",
    "Document the current state of the property with comprehensive photographs and video, noting any utility meter readings and any personal property left behind.",
    "Draft and send the Notice of Intention to Impose Claim on Security Deposit via certified mail to the tenant's last known address (and forwarding address, if any) within 30 days of the date the tenant vacated.",
    "If personal property was left behind, send a written Notice of Right to Reclaim Abandoned Property pursuant to Fla. Stat. 715.104, allowing the required 10 to 15 days for retrieval before disposal.",
    "Consult a qualified Florida landlord-tenant attorney to safely verify abandonment or proceed with a formal eviction to retake legal possession if there is any doubt about the tenant's return."
  ]
}

{
  "subject": "Notice Regarding Outstanding Utility Balance and Vacated Premises - [Property Address]",
  "body": "Dear [Tenant Name], It has come to our attention that you have vacated the premises at [Property Address] without providing formal notice. Our records indicate that there are outstanding utility balances associated with your tenancy. Under Florida law, we are preparing to process your security deposit. Please provide your current forwarding address as soon as possible so that we can mail you the official Notice of Intention to Impose Claim on Security Deposit, which will detail any deductions for unpaid utilities or other lease obligations. Additionally, if you left any personal belongings in the unit, please contact us immediately to arrange for their retrieval, as these items must be claimed within a limited timeframe under state law. Please contact our office at your earliest convenience to resolve these outstanding matters and to officially return the keys. Sincerely, [Landlord/Management Name], [Contact Information]"
}

{
  "risk_analysis": "As a landlord-operations analyst and not a lawyer, I must highlight that attempting to change the locks at this stage carries extreme legal and financial risk. Because no lease document was provided, there is inherent uncertainty regarding any specific contractual provisions; however, Florida law strictly supersedes any lease clause that would attempt to permit self-help. Under Fla. Stat. § 83.67, changing the locks, shutting off utilities, or otherwise excluding the tenant without a court order is an illegal self-help eviction. Doing so exposes you to severe statutory penalties, including liability for actual and consequential damages, or three months' rent (whichever is greater), plus the tenant's court costs and attorney's fees. Serving a 3-day notice is merely the preliminary demand for rent; it does not grant possession or authorize lockout measures.",
  "recommended_next_steps": [
    "Do not change the locks, terminate utilities, or interfere with the tenant's access to the property under any circumstances.",
    "Wait for the 3-day notice period to expire, ensuring you do not count the day of service, Saturdays, Sundays, or court-observed legal holidays.",
    "Consult with a licensed Florida landlord-tenant attorney to review the 3-day notice for technical accuracy before proceeding.",
    "If the tenant fails to pay or vacate by the deadline, have your attorney file a formal eviction complaint for possession in the local county court.",
    "Only change the locks after obtaining a final judgment for possession and once the sheriff has executed a formal writ of possession."
  ]
}
